1. What is a static method in Java?
-->A static method is a method declared with static that belongs to the class, not objects.

    👉 It can be called without creating an object.
    
    class Demo {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("Hello");
        }
    }


2. Can a static method access instance variables? Why or why not?
-->❌ No, it cannot directly access instance variables
    👉 Because:
    Static methods are class-level
    Instance variables belong to objects
    No object = no instance data
    
    ✔ But possible using object:
    
    class Demo {
        int x = 10;
    
        static void show() {
            Demo obj = new Demo();
            System.out.println(obj.x); // allowed
        }
    }



3. Can we call a static method using an object?
-->✅ Yes (but not recommended)
    Demo obj = new Demo();
    obj.show();  // Works, but bad practice
    👉 Best practice:
    Demo.show();



4. What happens if we declare a static method with the same signature in a subclass?
-->👉 This is called method hiding, NOT overriding.
    Depends on reference type, not object
    class Parent {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("Parent");
        }
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("Child");
        }
    }
    Parent obj = new Child();
    obj.show();  // Output: Parent



5. Why can’t we use this keyword inside a static method?
-->❌ Because:
    this refers to current object
    Static methods do not belong to any object
    
    👉 No object → no this



6. Can we overload static methods?
-->✅ Yes
    👉 Same method name, different parameters
    
    class Demo {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("No args");
        }
    
        static void show(int x) {
            System.out.println(x);
        }
    }



7. Can we override static methods? Explain with example.
-->❌ No (true overriding is not possible)
    
    👉 Static methods are not polymorphic
    
    ✔ It is method hiding
    
    class A {
        static void display() {
            System.out.println("A");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        static void display() {
            System.out.println("B");
        }
    }
    
    public class Test {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            A obj = new B();
            obj.display(); // A (not B)
        }
    }



8. What is the difference between a static method and an instance method?
-->
| Static Method                        | Instance Method       |
| ------------------------------------ | --------------------- |
| Belongs to class                     | Belongs to object     |
| No object needed                     | Object required       |
| Cannot access instance data directly | Can access everything |
| No `this` keyword                    | Uses `this`           |



9. When should you make a method static?
-->👉 Make it static when:
    Logic does not depend on object data
    Utility/helper methods
    Common functionality
    ✔ Examples:
    Math.sqrt()
    Integer.parseInt()



10. Can a static method call another static method?
-->✅ Yes, directly
    
    class Demo {
        static void method1() {
            System.out.println("Method 1");
        }
    
        static void method2() {
            method1(); // direct call
        }
    }


